se the result is not reliable."},{k:"step",a:"Engine",i:"Stabilize at established power ≥ 3 minutes"},{k:"step",a:"Record (avoid parallax)",i:"Torque (%), TOT (°C) — repeat for other engine"},{k:"step",a:"Chart limit TOT",i:"Obtain from Fig 5-1 (torque, PA, OAT)"},{k:"step",a:"ΔTOT",i:"Chart limit TOT − measured TOT"},{k:"note",t:"Acceptable when measured TOT ≤ chart limit TOT. If greater, repeat with 10% higher torque (if possible). If still failing in low/no wind, repeat in a hover with enough height."},{k:"warn",t:"When performing the power check at a hover and the online engine fails, both engines are considered inoperative — an emergency power-off landing shall be made."},{k:"step",a:"Results",i:"Record in the helicopter documents"}],notes:["Interval: at least every 100 flying hours (Category A: 50 hrs), or when abnormal engine function is suspected.","Max permissible ΔTOT change between two consecutive checks: 20 °C. Greater change → maintenance action.","Below −35 °C the cold weather kit 117-80020 shall be installed and operational.","Cross-ref: Training Manual — Power Plant (CH 6, p. 6-96…6-100)."]},{id:"inflight-power-check",cat:"powerchecks",group:"Power Assurance",title:"Inflight Power Check (TOT)",kind:"procedure",ref:{src:"FM",loc:"§5.6.4 · Fig 5-2 · p. 5-8…5-9",rev:"8"},topWarning:"Established for twin engine operation only. Performing the check single-engine (second engine in idle) will give incorrect results.",indications:["Twin-engine check, engines trimmed asymmetrically. Checks cruise power levels against the Section 5 charts — not a substitute for the ground check when one is required before flight."],blocks:[{k:"step",a:"Height above ground > 500 ft",i:"Attain (preferably minimum turbulence)"},{k:"step",a:"Steady level flight",i:"Establish — up to 8000 ft: 110 KIAS or max cruise or VNE−10, whichever is less; above 8000 ft: 90 KIAS or max cruise or VNE−10, whichever is less"},{k:"step",a:"Bleed air heating (engine to be checked)",i:"OFF"},{k:"ste