-BK117-60-111)"},{k:"Gross mass ≤ 3000 kg",v:"15 000 ft"},{k:"Gross mass > 3000 kg",v:"10 000 ft  (12 000 ft if OAT < −30 °C)"},{k:"HIGE, takeoff & landing",v:"17 000 ft DA or 15 000 ft PA — whichever is less"},{head:"Max operating altitude — S/N 7253 & subsequent (or after S/B-MBB-BK117-60-111)"},{k:"Gross mass ≤ 3000 kg",v:"18 000 ft"},{k:"Gross mass > 3000 kg",v:"10 000 ft  (12 000 ft if OAT < −30 °C)"},{k:"HIGE, takeoff & landing",v:"17 000 ft DA or 18 000 ft PA — whichever is less"},{head:"All effectivities"},{k:"French-registered, JP-4 fuel",v:"7 000 ft"},{k:"Minimum air temperature",v:"−45 °C"},{k:"Maximum air temperature",v:"ISA + 35 °C (max +50 °C)"}],notes:["All altitudes are pressure altitude (PA) unless given as density altitude (DA).","Full envelope (varies with OAT & gross mass): Fig 2-3, p. 2-7. The high-altitude (hatched) area is permitted only with the High Altitude Kit (S/N 7253 & subsequent, or S/B-MBB-BK117-60-111 incorporated).","Pitot and static port heating ON when ambient temperature is below +4.5 °C and visible moisture is present.","Flight into icing conditions is prohibited; if entered unexpectedly, leave the icing zone the quickest possible way.","↗ Chart Analyst (Suite · §5): these altitude limits bound the §5 performance lookups (hover ceiling, height-velocity, power check). Confirm the planned altitude is within them before using the charts."]},{id:"wind-limits",cat:"limits",group:"Airspeed",title:"Sideward, Rearward & Crosswind Limits",kind:"keyvalue",ref:{src:"FM",loc:"§2.8.2 / §2.8.3 · p. 2-6",rev:"6"},pairs:[{head:"Sideward / rearward flight (demonstrated)"},{k:"DA ≤ 3000 ft",v:"up to 30 kt"},{k:"DA > 3000 ft",v:"up to 20 kt"},{head:"Crosswind — standard takeoff & landing (demonstrated)"},{k:"Crosswind component",v:"up to 17 kt"}],notes:["Sideward / crosswind-hover and rearward / tailwind-hover demonstrated to these speeds, by density altitude (DA).","17 kt is the demonstrated directional-controllability crosswind limit for standard takeoff and landing — see the Wind Component Chart (Section 1).","External-load operations have their own, more restrictive sideward limits — see the External Cargo Hook entry."]},{id:"ech-limits",cat:"supplements",group:"External Cargo Hook · FMS 10-2",title:"External Cargo Hook — Limits & Weights",kind:"keyvalue",ref:{src:"FM",loc:"FMS 10-2 §2 · p. 10-2-3…2-5",rev:"8"},pairs:[{k:"Max cargo hook load — assy 117-80101",v:"1200 kg"},{k:"Max cargo hook load — assy 117-80112",v:"1500 kg"},{k:"Max combined gross mass (helicopter + load)",v:"3500 kg"},{k:"Max airspeed — with external load",v:"100 kt"},{k:"Max airspeed — trailing unloaded hook",v:"70 kt"},{k:"Max demonstrated bank angle",v:"45°"},{k:"Sideward flight — right / left / rearward",v:"10 / 20 / 20 kt"},{k:"Point of load application (aft of datum)",v:"4385 mm"},{k:"Cargo hook assy mass",v:"14.32 kg"}],notes:["VFR “Class B rotorcraft/load combination”: the external load is jettisonable and is lifted free of land or water.","Attach the load only with a fixed ring of inner diameter 50–80 mm.","Flight with an empty net or unballasted sling is prohibited unless the operator's approved limits/procedures allow it.","Keep the distance between load and hook as short as possible. HOGE operations with external cargo should be flown heading into wind.","ECD strongly recommends restricting cargo-hook operations with persons to emergency situations only."]},{id:"ech-emergency",cat:"supplements",group:"External Cargo Hook · FMS 10-2",title:"Cargo Hook — Engine Failure / Load Jettison",kind:"procedure",ref:{src:"FM",loc:"FMS 10-2 §3 / §4 · p. 10-2-6…2-8",rev:"8"},lamps:[{caption:"HOOK",type:"caution"}],indications:["One engine fails while carrying an external load, or the load must be released in an emergency."],blocks:[{k:"note",t:"If one engine fails, the external load may have to be dumped. Refer to the single-engine performance diagrams, Section 5 of the basic Flight Manual."},{k:"phase",t:"Electrical Release (Normal)"},{k:"step",a:"Safety cover (CARGO HOOK REL. switch)",i:"Open"},{k:"step",a:"CARGO HOOK REL. switch (collective)",i:"Push forward — load releases when its mass overcomes the hook spring force"},{k:"warn",t:"Illumination of the HOOK caution light does not safely indicate that the cargo sling is detached from the hook."},{k:"phase",t:"Electrical Release Failure"},{k:"step",a:"Mechanical emergency release (foot-operated, RH door frame)",i:"Operate to release the load"}],notes:["HOOK caution light: illuminates while the cargo hook trails and no force greater than 50 N (5 kg) acts on the hook. The maximum trailing-unloaded airspeed of 70 kt must not be exceeded.","Opening the hook requires overcoming a spring force of approx. 50 N (5 kg); this force re-closes and locks the hook automatically."]},{id:"lrft-numbers",cat:"supplements",group:"Long Range Fuel Tank · FMS 10-3",title:"Long Range Fuel Tank — Numbers & Weights",kind:"keyvalue",ref:{src:"FM",loc:"FMS 10-3 §2 · p. 10-3-2…3-6",rev:"8"},pairs:[{k:"Usable fuel — per tank",v:"159.0 kg · 198.8 l"},{k:"Unusable fuel — per tank (cruise)",v:"1.0 kg · 1.2 l"},{k:"Total capacity — per tank",v:"160.0 kg · 200.0 l"},{k:"Capacity (US)",v:"52.8 US gal"},{k:"Fuel density basis",v:"0.8 kg/l"},{k:"Tank mass (empty, detachable portion)",v:"≈ 23 – 28.5 kg"}],notes:["Fuel transfer into the main tank is by gravity. Quantity is read on the main-tank indicator via the FUEL QTY-IND switch (LR TK-L / LR TK-R).","At low airspeed and/or extreme aft CG, unusable fuel rises to max 13.82 l (11.06 kg) per tank.","P/N 117-804381: two tanks may NOT be installed simultaneously. P/N 117-804401: two tanks permitted only when both are fixed in the most forward position. CG limits remain unchanged.","System switches LR FUEL TK L / R have positions EMER OP · OP · CL."]},{id:"lrft-emergency",cat:"supplements",group:"Long Range Fuel Tank · FMS 10-3",title:"Long Range Fuel Tank — Emergency / Malfunction",kind:"procedure",ref:{src:"FM",loc:"FMS 10-3 §3 · p. 10-3-3",rev:"8"},indications:["MN TK FREE indication does not come on although less than 200 kg is shown on the MN TANK FUEL QTY indicator, or an emergency landing is impending."],blocks:[{k:"phase",t:"MN TK FREE Indication Failure"},{k:"step",a:"Respective LR FUEL TK switch",i:"EMER OP (overrides the lock; valve opens immediately)"},{k:"phase",t:"Emergency Landing"},{k:"step",a:"Fuel",i:"Transfer as much as possible into the main tank"},{k:"warn",t:"In case of an emergency landing, set the respective LR FUEL TK switch to CL (close) prior to touchdown."}]},{id:"csas3-numbers",cat:"supplements",group:"3-Axis CSAS · FMS 10-32",title:"3-Axis CSAS — Numbers & Notes",kind:"keyvalue",ref:{src:"FM",loc:"FMS 10-32 · p. 10-32-1…32-7",rev:"1"},pairs:[{k:"System mass",v:"23.72 kg"},{k:"Arm (aft of datum)",v:"5100 mm"},{k:"Actuator authority (each axis)",v:"± 5%"},{k:"Part number",v:"117-88602 / 117-872701"}],notes:["Augments pitch, roll and yaw via the flight-control servo actuators; two independent subsystems (pitch/roll and yaw) on a common control panel.","All CSAS axes can be switched off simultaneously by the STABILIZATION CUTOFF pushbutton on the cyclic stick grip.","CG and limitations not contained in the supplement remain per the basic Flight Manual."]},{id:"csas3-pitchroll",cat:"supplements",group:"3-Axis CSAS · FMS 10-32",title:"3-Axis CSAS — PITCH / ROLL Caution",kind:"procedure",ref:{src:"FM",loc:"FMS 10-32 §3.1.1 · p. 10-32-2",rev:"1"},lamps:[{caption:"CSAS PITCH",type:"caution"},{caption:"CSAS ROLL",type:"caution"}],indications:["Malfunction of the respective CSAS axis","Change in respective axis control behavior"],blocks:[{k:"step",a:"Affected axis switch",i:"OFF"},{k:"note",t:"A pitch/roll axis failure might indicate a copilot's artificial-horizon malfunction. Check for the absence of a warning flag."}]},{id:"csas3-yaw",cat:"supplements",group:"3-Axis CSAS · FMS 10-32",title:"3-Axis CSAS — YAW Caution",kind:"procedure",ref:{src:"FM",loc:"FMS 10-32 §3.1 · p. 10-32-3",rev:"1"},lamps:[{caption:"CSAS YAW",type:"caution"}],indications:["Malfunction of the yaw axis","Change in yaw control behavior"],blocks:[{k:"warn",t:"Avoid hard and abrupt left/right pedal movements after pressing the STABILIZATION CUTOFF pushbutton."},{k:"note",t:"A yaw axis failure might indicate a pilot's artificial-horizon malfunction. Check for the absence of a warning flag."},{k:"step",a:"STABILIZATION CUTOFF pushbutton",i:"Press"},{k:"step",a:"PITCH and ROLL switches",i:"OFF, then ON"}]},{id:"csas3-runaway",cat:"supplements",group:"3-Axis CSAS · FMS 10-32",title:"3-Axis CSAS — Pitch/Roll Actuator Runaway",kind:"procedure",ref:{src:"FM",loc:"FMS 10-32 §3.2.1 · p. 10-32-3",rev:"1"},indications:["Sudden attitude change","Affected axis caution light comes on"],blocks:[{k:"note",t:"When operating near the ground, remain attentive — an actuator runaway could result in a loss of altitude."},{k:"step",a:"STABILIZATION CUTOFF pushbutton",i:"Press"},{k:"step",a:"Non-affected axes",i:"Reengage"},{k:"note",t:"The helicopter may yaw slightly when reengaging the yaw CSAS."}]},{id:"csasyaw-numbers",cat:"supplements",group:"Yaw CSAS · FMS 10-41",title:"Yaw CSAS — Notes",kind:"keyvalue",ref:{src:"FM",loc:"FMS 10-41 · p. 10-41-1",rev:"0"},pairs:[{k:"Part number",v:"117-88610"},{k:"Hydraulic supply",v:"System II"}],notes:["Improves control and dynamic stability around the yaw axis; eases directional control and reduces the effect of turbulence.","The Yaw CSAS can be switched off via the STABILIZATION CUTOFF pushbutton on the cyclic stick grip.","If hydraulic system I fails and an automatic changeover to system II occurs, the hydraulic supply to the yaw actuator is cut off and the Yaw CSAS becomes inoperative.","CG and limitations not contained in the supplement remain per the basic Flight Manual."]},{id:"csasyaw-caution",cat:"supplements",group:"Yaw CSAS · FMS 10-41",title:"Yaw CSAS — CSAS YAW Caution",kind:"procedure",ref:{src:"FM",loc:"FMS 10-41 §3.1.1 · p. 10-41-2",rev:"0"},lamps:[{caption:"CSAS YAW",type:"caution"}],indications:["Malfunction of the yaw axis","Change in yaw control behavior"],blocks:[{k:"warn",t:"Avoid hard and abrupt left/right pedal movements after pressing the STABILIZATION CUTOFF pushbutton."},{k:"note",t:"A yaw axis failure might indicate a pilot's artificial-horizon malfunction. Check for the absence of a warning flag."},{k:"step",a:"STABILIZATION CUTOFF pushbutton",i:"Press"}]},{id:"cata-limits",cat:"supplements",group:"Category A Operations · FMS 11-1",title:"Category A — Limitations",kind:"keyvalue",ref:{src:"FM",loc:"FMS 11-1 §A.2 / §B.2 · p. 11-1-4 / 11-1-13",rev:"8"},pairs:[{k:"Max altitude — takeoff & landing (Clear Heliport)",v:"13 000 ft DA"},{k:"Power check interval",v:"≤ 50 flying hours"},{k:"Tailwind takeoff / landing",v:"Prohibited"},{k:"Radar altimeter",v:"Required (operative)"},{k:"Upper gross mass limit",v:"3350 kg"}],notes:["Category A operations are prohibited if the power check is not satisfactory; a power-trend monitoring shall be established.","Category A takeoff and landing are prohibited with opened/removed doors (FMS 11-3). A cockpit door may be opened/held at low airspeed close to the ground to observe ground clearance before touchdown.","The radar altimeter is used to determine the heights of the takeoff and landing decision points (TDP / LDP)."]},{id:"cata-speeds",cat:"supplements",group:"Category A Operations · FMS 11-1",title:"Category A — Speeds & Decision Points",kind:"keyvalue",ref:{src:"FM",loc:"FMS 11-1 §A.1.3 · p. 11-1-3",rev:"8"},pairs:[{k:"VTOSS — takeoff safety speed",v:"50 KIAS"},{k:"VY — best rate of climb",v:"65 KIAS"},{k:"TDP (helipad / VTOL)",v:"140 ft AHE"},{k:"Takeoff flight path — 35 ft / VTOSS / +rate",v:"Segment I → 200 ft, Segment II → 1000 ft"},{k:"Max takeoff & landing gross mass",v:"Fig B1 (Clear) / Fig C1 (VTOL)"}],notes:["VTOSS assures ≥ 100 fpm rate of climb on 2.5-min power (OEI) at the max gross mass for the ambient condition.","Abbreviations: AHE abov